content.description:
"To the left of the fin, yawn up cracks through a couple of lieback moves near the top." 

  Mike Farris, Rock Climbing Minnesota and Wisconsin, p. 172
content.protection: Surprisingly, there are two bolts at the top of this buttress.
content.location: The obvious buttress Just down river from the Keyhole Area

content.description:

  Mike Farris, Rock Climbing Minnesota and Wisconsin, p. 172
content.protection: Surprisingly, there are two bolts at the top of this buttress.
content.location: The obvious buttress Just down river from the Keyhole Area

content.description:
"Right of the fin, left of the lieback corner. Start up the slab use the thin crack to reach the upper cracks." 

  Mike Farris, Rock Climbing Minnesota and Wisconsin, p. 172
content.protection: Surprisingly, there are two bolts at the top of this buttress.
content.location: The obvious buttress Just down river from the Keyhole Area

content.description: Face climbing with a handful of options that climbs up through a crack that splits an overhang.
content.location: Just upstream from the base of Delicate Dihedral.

content.description:
"The easiest version takes a crack on the right side of the face up to a ledge. Step across to footholds above the overhang. Variations: Lieback the corner, exit left (5.7) or straight up (5.11ish)"  

  Mike Farris, Rock Climbing Minnesota and Wisconsin, p. 172
content.protection: Surprisingly, there are two bolts at the top of this buttress.
content.location: The obvious buttress Just down river from the Keyhole Area

content.description: The top of this route features some small overhangs to climb over using big holds while the bottom offers some face climbing.
content.protection: There are lots of cracks on top of this route to set up top rope or else sling a couple of big features in the rock.
content.location: "Just before reaching the Delicate Dihedral descent gully is a face with a couple of small overhangs. Walk around and you can get a view of it from the various overlooks, or from the top of Dogleg Crack."   Mike Farris, Rock Climbing Minnesota and Wisconsin, p. 172
